This is probably also worth restricting the rare ones out. I also got rid of the NAs:

ufo_data %>%
  group_by(UFO_shape) %>%
  mutate(shape_count = n()) %>%
  filter(shape_count > 500, !is.na(UFO_shape)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
ggplot() +
    geom_bar(aes(x = UFO_shape)) +
               coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "UFO Data by Shape", x = "UFO Shape")

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Im not sure why this isnt doing what I want. I wanted to see the number of UFO Sightings in NY distributed by UFO Shape.

If youre wanting a dot plot for shape counts, youll need a count value. You could generate one using a mutate and then pass to ggplot:

ufo_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(UFO_shape), !is.na(`state/province`), `state/province` == "ny") %>%
  group_by(UFO_shape) %>%
  mutate(Shape_Count = n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot((aes(x = UFO_shape, y = Shape_Count))) +
  geom_point() +
  coord_flip()  +
  labs(title = "NY State UFO sightings")

(Also, a smoother here doesnt make sense.)

ufo_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(UFO_shape), !is.na(`state/province`), `state/province` == "ny") %>%
ggplot() +
      geom_bar(aes(x = UFO_shape)) +
               coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "NY State UFO Data by Shape", x = "UFO Shape", y = "Number in NY")

That looks better!
